First of all, every time I asked for a toasted bagel, it came out cold, too chewy and you could tell a bagel is just not fresh. Secondly, the wait for a simple toasted bagel with cream cheese is just way too long, even when there aren’t any lines. Why does it take so long to make a bagel, especially if you barely toast it? During my most recent trip I ordered a toasted BLT mini bagel with avocado and cheese. For some reason the mini version cost just as much as the regular size ($9 and change), even though it’s half the bagel and can fit half the toppings.  I had a meeting to get to and was anxious about the time after waiting for 10 minutes, especially given there was NO ONE else in line! I asked the cashier several times if she knew when it’d be ready and she disappeared to the kitchen for a few minutes then came back with no answer. I also saw the woman in the kitchen stop making a sandwich and started mopping the floor, then went back to finish it. Ugh.  After over 15 minutes, I finally paid and ran out the door and got on the train and when I opened up the wrapping there wasn’t even cheese on it! So not worth the wait or the price. Sadly can’t recommend this place anymore which is a shame as it used to be my favorite!

Ordered a dozen bagels with cream cheese and butter (enough for who wanted whatever on the side) as a thank you to the guys for the hospitality while we worked at a condo building in Brooklyn. I told the guy who took the order what it was for but no plastic utensils, napkins or plates. I Al's mentioned jobsite. I ordered myself a dark toasted everything bagel with tuna, thin tomato and black pepper. Well, not toasted at all. No pepper. I guess this fits the vein of the folks who cannot appreciate texture in bread. Then, only the cop out tuna salad one style I can give a 7 out of 10 for a bit of lemon (or I hope it is lemon) zing. Not zest, but zing. The stuff came, good looking bagels with a tight hole but not cooked enough, a common issue with those not brought up eating bagels or any good bread for that matter (thinking everything should look like a hot dog bun) I'm sure it is not the owner but surely the workers who are there solely for the money. But I asked for dark toasted and yes, it does matter. My life must be pretty easy if I can complain about the degree of toasti-ness. I should be happy I even have food. Chaulk it up to the new wave of migrant workers that has undermined the staples of NYC fast food: bagels, pizza and deli. Besides, when I was a kid the owner and his/her family worked the floor. Yeah yeah, so you recon I am thanks for peeking.

Asked for a well toasted bagel and got a completely burned one. Well toasted doesn't mean burned. I had to remove half the bagel because it tasted so bad. Delicious bagels and a popular spot in Williamsburg on a Sunday morning. Service is quick though, so don't let the long line discourage you. They were out of mini bagels, so I got a regular sized Everything Bagel with Vegetable Cream Cheese.  There are four stools by a counter at the front window, and we were lucky to get a seat to enjoy our breakfast. The bagel was super fresh and soft and chewy with a slight hint of sweetness that I enjoyed. It was not really toasted enough if you like it crispy, but I was fine with the softness of it. The cream cheese was your basic vegetable cream cheese, but the bagel was definitely the star of the show.  I would definitely come back and have another bagel and try the whitefish or a sandwich with it next time. Prices are a bit on the steep side, but outside of that, it was a delicious breakfast and I will be back if I am in the neighborhood.
